To assess if you should continue against operate the bike business, you must compare the anticipated earnings to the anticipated pay of an accountant and the rental revenue from renting the store. The anticipated revenues from the operation of the bike shop are: Revenue minus expenses equals $80,000 per year. The average annual income for an accountant is $40,000. The anticipated annual rental revenue from the shop is $50,000. It looks that managing the bike shop would be more lucrative than becoming an accountant or leasing the business. The anticipated profit of $80,000 per year from operating the bike shop is more than the anticipated pay of a certified public accountant or rental income. Therefore, it would be in your best interest to continue operating the bike shop. 